1
00:00:00,638 --> 00:00:30,274
Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambhodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:32,195 --> 00:00:40,042
So we've been going through this Anathalaka no Sutta, the discourse on the characteristic of not-self.

3
00:00:40,984 --> 00:00:47,231
And if you remember, the first teaching is concerning to do with control.

4
00:00:47,250 --> 00:00:53,417
If this is me, then I should be able to do what I want with it.

5
00:00:54,237 --> 00:01:00,884
This is a key sort of understanding at that time as to what a soul or a self was.

6
00:01:01,354 --> 00:01:04,158
a soul or a self was completely in control of itself.

7
00:01:05,179 --> 00:01:17,612
So if you look at any part of our experience as a human being, whether it's the body or thoughts or emotions, you can see from this sitting that we've just done that they arise also because of themselves.

8
00:01:18,274 --> 00:01:23,618
Even though we have a certain control, we discover that actually we don't have total control.

9
00:01:24,379 --> 00:01:27,623
And the argument would be if you can't control it, it's not you.

10
00:01:28,665 --> 00:01:29,646
It's got another center.

11
00:01:29,766 --> 00:01:30,466
It's got its own

12
00:01:30,986 --> 00:02:00,066
center of control but he also points out that even that is not a self as if it were something substantial it's also something ephemeral, changing and that's the next point the next point about the soul or the self is that it's permanent so if we look at any of our experience whether it's physical, mental, emotional it arises and passes away

13
00:02:00,501 --> 00:02:04,766
So it can't be a soul or a self or anything permanent.

14
00:02:04,786 --> 00:02:07,647
And that would be one of the definitions of a soul or a self.

15
00:02:07,668 --> 00:02:08,508
That's the point.

16
00:02:08,688 --> 00:02:11,752
It's how you define a soul or a self.

17
00:02:11,771 --> 00:02:20,218
And then, of course, he asks the question, well, if it's impermanent, does that bring a sense of dissatisfaction or satisfaction?

18
00:02:20,278 --> 00:02:21,941
Well, it's unsatisfactory, isn't it?

19
00:02:22,401 --> 00:02:27,485
It might be satisfactory if something is painful and then it passes away.

20
00:02:27,665 --> 00:02:29,486
But when it's happy, we can't hold on to it.

21
00:02:29,546 --> 00:02:30,187
That's also

22
00:02:30,538 --> 00:02:32,200
It can be unsatisfactory.

23
00:02:32,741 --> 00:02:38,991
So in the discourse here, he's actually explaining these three characteristics of existence, right?

24
00:02:39,010 --> 00:02:44,680
They're the fundamental characteristics of existence that he's pointing to, to discover our true nature.

25
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:55,314
When we perceive things as they really are, we also begin to see what there really is, okay?

26
00:02:57,403 --> 00:03:25,807
so now what I want to do is to read another discourse which gives another side of the Buddhist teachings because this is an intellectual exposition but he also has a way of expressing things through imagery we'll come to that but in this particular discourse he gave it to his five companions so this was after he'd become fully awakened he searched for them found them in Benares present day Varanasi and at Isipetana

27
00:03:26,766 --> 00:03:29,889
Sarnath, excuse me, Sarnath, is the Pathanapak.

28
00:03:29,909 --> 00:03:43,085
And so the story goes, when he gave them a talk, then they went on arms round, and after they'd eaten and had a rest, he gave this talk, and all of them became fully liberated.

29
00:03:43,866 --> 00:03:48,270
And I just want to read the end of it, which gives you the formula in which this is said, you see.

30
00:03:48,890 --> 00:03:54,377
So, seeing thus, you see, the instructed noble disciple said,

31
00:03:54,610 --> 00:04:09,985
becomes disenchanted with form, that's the body as well, disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perceptions, disenchanted with volitional formations, so those are your thoughts and emotions, and disenchanted with consciousness.

32
00:04:10,245 --> 00:04:17,132
See, that word disenchanted, no longer caught up in the enchantment of the world, you're not bewitched by it.

33
00:04:18,572 --> 00:04:22,677
Now, when we become disenchanted, the next step is to become dispassionate.

34
00:04:23,314 --> 00:04:31,446
It doesn't mean to say that you end up being a sort of emotionally void, a sort of a numb blob.

35
00:04:31,946 --> 00:04:36,651
It just means that you don't get passionate about things in the wrong way.

36
00:04:38,314 --> 00:04:43,420
Being angry, holding on to things, attachment, you become dispassionate.

37
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:46,845
And it's through this process of dispassion that we're liberated.

38
00:04:49,007 --> 00:04:49,608
Dispassion.

39
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:55,665
So the insight creates a different relationship of disenchantment.

40
00:04:56,004 --> 00:05:08,716
This disenchantment affects our relationship with the world, which is the way we experience the world ourselves, which leads to a sense of equanimity, a sense of ease with the world.

41
00:05:09,057 --> 00:05:11,218
That's the dispassionate part.

42
00:05:11,238 --> 00:05:14,661
And that's, when it's taken to the limit, that's the liberation of the mind.

43
00:05:14,841 --> 00:05:16,463
That's the liberation of consciousness.

44
00:05:16,783 --> 00:05:17,605
Probably a better word.

45
00:05:19,610 --> 00:05:25,956
Although, as you know, the word I prefer is the knowing, that which knows, you see, the Buddha within, the Buddha within.

46
00:05:27,158 --> 00:05:38,430
And once that's done, he understands, it is lovely, you see, destroyed his birth, see, this rebirth, the spiritual life has been lived, what has been done has been done.

47
00:05:38,612 --> 00:05:39,913
Can you feel the relief in that?

48
00:05:40,653 --> 00:05:42,295
See?

49
00:05:42,315 --> 00:05:47,000
It's like when you have to redecorate a house, you see, and you finish it and it's all very nice and beautiful.

50
00:05:47,452 --> 00:05:50,096
And you say what has been done has been done.

51
00:05:50,115 --> 00:05:52,398
See, a sense of relief and satisfaction.

52
00:05:53,139 --> 00:05:56,062
There is no more coming back to any state of becoming.

53
00:05:57,783 --> 00:06:01,206
This constant rebirthing business.

54
00:06:01,226 --> 00:06:14,379
Now you have to be careful here because at the spiritual level the rebirthing means the recreation of this self which is recreating the wrong relationship to the world.

55
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:15,081
See?

56
00:06:15,668 --> 00:06:18,512
You have to remember that when the Buddha was liberated, he didn't disappear.

57
00:06:19,093 --> 00:06:19,713
He was still there.

58
00:06:19,774 --> 00:06:23,259
He acted as he was there, fully liberated, walking around as even being.

59
00:06:23,899 --> 00:06:31,651
So whenever we read this end of becoming or end of being, as some people translate it, we think of annihilation.

60
00:06:32,291 --> 00:06:33,072
It's obviously not.

61
00:06:34,555 --> 00:06:44,088
What's annihilated, the Buddha's clear about this, what is annihilated is that wrong view, the delusion, and with it, all sense of attachment to the world,

62
00:06:44,591 --> 00:06:47,475
and all sense of aversion or fear of the world.

63
00:06:48,036 --> 00:06:49,458
That's what disappears completely.

64
00:06:52,362 --> 00:07:10,684
And then finally, that is what the Blessed One said, elated, those monks delighted in the Blessed One's statement, and while this discourse was being spoken, the minds of those monks of the group of five were liberated from the taints by non-clinging.

65
00:07:12,571 --> 00:07:18,478
Now the taint is just another word of saying all those things in us which are produced by this wrong thinking.

66
00:07:19,420 --> 00:07:20,240
Okay?

67
00:07:20,261 --> 00:07:24,326
And that non-clinging is just another way of saying dispassion.

68
00:07:25,507 --> 00:07:26,069
See?

69
00:07:26,088 --> 00:07:28,451
So you can bring this into your daily life.

70
00:07:28,552 --> 00:07:39,586
Every time you have a sort of a compulsion to do something, to have that biscuit and a cup of tea, you see, just hang on there.

71
00:07:39,607 --> 00:07:41,129
Just wait till it passes away.

72
00:07:41,490 --> 00:07:41,649
You see?

73
00:07:42,305 --> 00:07:45,949
What's the mind when there's no desire in it, you see?

74
00:07:46,569 --> 00:07:52,235
And the more that we move towards that state, the more we're developing the state of contentment.

75
00:07:53,896 --> 00:07:56,480
Contentment is a quality of the Buddha mind.

76
00:07:57,620 --> 00:07:59,942
Contentment and joy.

77
00:08:03,226 --> 00:08:07,870
So, let's see how he expresses this in imagery.

78
00:08:08,271 --> 00:08:09,492
Because he often says,

79
00:08:09,877 --> 00:08:16,648
there are people for whom imagery works better than an intellectual dry approach.

80
00:08:16,668 --> 00:08:21,615
So this is on one occasion, he was dwelling at Ayodhya on the bank of the river Ganges.

81
00:08:21,634 --> 00:08:24,399
And there the Blessed One addressed the monks thus.

82
00:08:25,019 --> 00:08:30,788
In the scriptures where you come across Bhikkhu, I can't remember what that figure of speech is called.

83
00:08:30,807 --> 00:08:34,734
You know when you say things like all hands on deck, meaning all people.

84
00:08:34,754 --> 00:08:37,658
So this is when the commentaries tell us that

85
00:08:38,092 --> 00:08:41,638
When the Buddha uses the word monks, he's referring to anybody who's listening.

86
00:08:43,841 --> 00:08:59,522
So suppose that this river Ganges was carrying along a great lump of foam and a man with good sight would inspect it, ponder it and carefully investigate it and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

87
00:09:00,322 --> 00:09:03,527
For what substance could there be in a lump of foam?

88
00:09:04,672 --> 00:09:19,653
So to monks, whatever kind of form there is, remember that's the body, whether past or future or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near.

89
00:09:21,615 --> 00:09:34,273
And the meditator inspects it, ponders it and carefully investigates it and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial for what substance could there be in form?

90
00:09:35,519 --> 00:10:00,666
now you see we know from our subatomic physics that this body is just a mass of energy there's nothing substantial in it at all but that's not how we experience it you trap your finger in the door it's definitely got substance but in reality it's nothing it's just frazzled energy walking around wonderful stuff now suppose that in the autumn when it is raining

91
00:10:00,932 --> 00:10:06,660
and the big raindrops are falling, and a water bubble arises and bursts on the surface of the water.

92
00:10:07,763 --> 00:10:16,535
A man with good sight would inspect it, ponder it, and carefully investigate it, and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, and insubstantial.

93
00:10:16,897 --> 00:10:19,259
For what substance could there be in a water bubble?

94
00:10:20,522 --> 00:10:30,736
So too, whatever kind of feeling there is, whether past, future, or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior,

95
00:10:31,087 --> 00:10:41,283
Far or near, a monk inspects it, ponders it, carefully investigates it, and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

96
00:10:41,845 --> 00:10:44,828
For what substance could there be in feeling?

97
00:10:46,851 --> 00:10:52,541
Now, when we have a feeling, it presents itself as something hard, you see.

98
00:10:52,581 --> 00:10:58,850
Feeling, say, if you have a pain in the knee or some pain in the body caused by an emotional state.

99
00:10:59,388 --> 00:11:04,033
At first, it feels hard because of that identity with it, you see.

100
00:11:04,094 --> 00:11:05,254
That's what hardens it.

101
00:11:05,936 --> 00:11:09,139
This, you know, I am suffering, you see.

102
00:11:09,159 --> 00:11:15,548
But actually, when you go into this meditation, as we've just done, and you can feel it, you can see there's nothing there.

103
00:11:15,587 --> 00:11:19,873
Once you get into the texture of it, it's got no substance.

104
00:11:20,914 --> 00:11:22,416
There's nothing in it at all.

105
00:11:22,475 --> 00:11:26,981
It's just a passing state of different sensations, you see.

106
00:11:30,488 --> 00:11:37,998
Suppose that in the last month of the hot season, at high noon, a shimmering mirage appears.

107
00:11:39,399 --> 00:11:46,769
Now a man with good sight would inspect it, ponder it, and carefully investigate it, and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

108
00:11:46,869 --> 00:11:49,471
For what substance could there be in a mirage?

109
00:11:50,774 --> 00:11:57,001
So too, monks, whatever kind of perception there is, whether past, future, or present, internal or external,

110
00:11:57,471 --> 00:12:27,192
gross or subtle inferior or superior far or near a monk inspects it ponders it carefully investigates it and it would appear to him to be void hollow insubstantial for what substance could there be in perception now when we perceive something that is a correlative something which is an image in the mind which relates to what you're looking at so we know that the eye when it's looking at a picture

111
00:12:27,475 --> 00:12:30,860
is just moving around at enormous speeds, picking up little pixels.

112
00:12:31,500 --> 00:12:38,451
And it's coming back into the brain, into the mind-brain complex, and it's creating a constant picture, you see.

113
00:12:40,695 --> 00:12:46,023
And then, in that amazing way, it then projects it back onto the picture.

114
00:12:46,663 --> 00:12:55,356
So what we're actually seeing is the picture in the mind being projected onto the picture that we're supposedly looking at.

115
00:12:55,376 --> 00:12:56,958
And therefore, it's a mirage.

116
00:12:57,547 --> 00:12:59,610
It doesn't actually exist.

117
00:13:00,571 --> 00:13:02,153
We're not actually seeing that picture.

118
00:13:02,173 --> 00:13:04,537
What we're seeing is what the mind's creating.

119
00:13:06,178 --> 00:13:07,681
That's a lovely image of a mirage.

120
00:13:10,325 --> 00:13:22,322
Suppose a man needing heartwood, that's the very middle of the wood of a tree, seeking heartwood, wandering in search of heartwood, would take a sharp axe and enter a forest.

121
00:13:23,197 --> 00:13:28,705
There he would see the trunk of a large banana tree, straight, fresh, without a fruit bud core.

122
00:13:29,846 --> 00:13:34,193
He would cut it down at the root, cut off the crown, and unroll the coil.

123
00:13:35,034 --> 00:13:39,902
As he unrolled the coil, he would not find even softwood, let alone heartwood.

124
00:13:40,844 --> 00:13:48,315
A man with good sight would inspect it, ponder it, and carefully investigate it, and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

125
00:13:48,794 --> 00:13:51,820
For what substance could there be in the trunk of a banana tree?

126
00:13:53,655 --> 00:14:09,038
So two monks, whatever kind of volitional formations there are, whether past, future or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near, a monk inspects them, ponders them, carefully investigates them.

127
00:14:09,437 --> 00:14:13,924
And as he investigates them, they appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

128
00:14:14,446 --> 00:14:17,909
For what substance could there be in volitional formations?

129
00:14:17,931 --> 00:14:21,115
Now, if you think of our emotional thought life,

130
00:14:22,376 --> 00:14:23,958
it's layer upon layer isn't it?

131
00:14:23,999 --> 00:14:50,224
it's just coming up you're sitting here you know and suddenly off on a dream so if you think of something that makes a little bit more more immediate is an onion you see as you keep peeling the levels of an onion when you get to the middle of it there's nothing there so all these emotional states we get all these thought patterns you see they're all coming up and they're all just going away and there's nothing in them there's nothing substantial see

132
00:14:52,582 --> 00:15:18,422
substantial good image yeah now suppose that a magician or a magician's apprentice would display a magical illusion at a crossroads and a man with good sight would inspect it ponder it and carefully investigate it and it would appear to him to be void hollow and substantial for what substance could there be in a magical illusion so too monks whatever kind of consciousness there is

133
00:15:18,789 --> 00:15:26,701
whether past, future or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near.

134
00:15:26,841 --> 00:15:34,672
A monk inspects it, ponders it, carefully investigates it, and it would appear to him to be void, hollow, insubstantial.

135
00:15:35,072 --> 00:15:37,655
For what substance could there be in consciousness?

136
00:15:37,917 --> 00:15:47,429
Now, the English translation here is a bit strange and is not quite right because consciousness has so many meanings these days.

137
00:15:48,288 --> 00:16:17,332
even in the Buddha's discourses the word consciousness is used variously depending on the context and that's the same with other words because he's having to use the concepts of his time to get across his new understanding and there's always that difficulty of trying to say something and being misunderstood because people hear the word and hear it from another position and hear it from another meaning

138
00:16:18,105 --> 00:16:29,817
So what's understood here is that a perception is some sort of word, a label that we put on things, and it's also some sort of image.

139
00:16:30,216 --> 00:16:34,441
So when you see an apple, you have an image of it, and you also have a word for it.

140
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:39,544
And those all congregate to, shall we say, a perceptual process.

141
00:16:40,446 --> 00:16:48,113
This perceptual process grows with the subtlety of your thinking.

142
00:16:48,328 --> 00:17:15,093
large concepts like democracy and freedom and all that which remain in the mind as perceptions, conceptions all this has to, as it were, come forward onto something that we can see so that would be like a television screen and at that point there's a cognition and that's what he's talking about so just as on the screen of your computer I mean, what is it?

143
00:17:15,212 --> 00:17:16,934
is there any substance there?

144
00:17:17,708 --> 00:17:18,648
It's just a picture, isn't it?

145
00:17:19,950 --> 00:17:23,574
Or when you're watching a film in a cinema.

146
00:17:23,733 --> 00:17:31,342
It looks real, but what it is, it's just a screen, as we know with photons and all that, but there's no substance to it.

147
00:17:31,842 --> 00:17:34,183
Even a 3D film, there's no substance to it.

148
00:17:34,845 --> 00:17:38,628
And that's a lovely, a magical illusion, you see.

149
00:17:38,689 --> 00:17:40,411
It's a magical illusion.

150
00:17:41,491 --> 00:17:44,074
Now, it wouldn't be a problem, but we identify with it.

151
00:17:44,295 --> 00:17:45,915
We say, I am my consciousness.

152
00:17:45,935 --> 00:17:47,698
I think, therefore I am, and all that sort of stuff.

153
00:17:48,049 --> 00:17:49,731
That's the problem.

154
00:17:49,751 --> 00:17:54,960
But when we discover we're not that, then we become dispassionate about it.

155
00:17:54,980 --> 00:17:59,625
We don't get so involved, we don't get so attached to the world, and the suffering disappears.

156
00:18:04,492 --> 00:18:14,326
So now, as usual, he says, when the instructed noble disciple becomes disenchanted, see this word disenchanted, not being caught up with,

157
00:18:14,813 --> 00:18:23,765
Form disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with volitional formations, and disenchanted with consciousness.

158
00:18:23,825 --> 00:18:27,170
And becoming disenchanted, he becomes dispassionate.

159
00:18:27,190 --> 00:18:29,653
Through dispassion, his mind is liberated.

160
00:18:29,792 --> 00:18:33,357
And when it is liberated, there comes the knowledge it is liberated.

161
00:18:33,758 --> 00:18:34,499
He understands.

162
00:18:34,960 --> 00:18:38,345
Destroyed his birth, the spiritual life has been lived.

163
00:18:38,785 --> 00:18:41,409
What had to be done has been done.

164
00:18:41,628 --> 00:18:42,390
Oh, what a reliever.

165
00:18:42,826 --> 00:18:46,375
And there is no more coming back to any state of becoming.

166
00:18:49,201 --> 00:18:55,215
Here ends the discourse on the quality of not-self by the Buddha.

167
00:18:55,797 --> 00:19:10,452
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that they will lead you to your liberation sooner rather than later.

